HEADLINE: HUNGARY: CHAIN REACTION POSSIBLE AFTER NUCLEAR PLANT <br>
ACCIDENT - OPPOSITION <br>
<br>
<br>
BODY: <br>
The opposition deputy chairman of the parliamentary environmental <br>
protection committee, Zoltan Illes, has said that unless the damaged <br>
fuel rods are removed a Chernobyl-like &quot;chain reaction&quot; could start <br>
in the Paks nuclear power station. Illes called for international <br>
experts, adding that Hungarian experts were afraid to speak out. He <br>
accused the management of misleading the public about radiation <br>
levels. Meanwhile, the prime minister asked for an &quot;emergency report&quot; <br>
on developments at Paks. The following is excerpt from report by <br>
Pannon Radio 8 May and Hungarian Kossuth Radio on 9 May: <br>
<br>
The prime minister Peter Medgyessy has asked for an emergency report <br>
on developments at the Paks southern Hungary nuclear power station, <br>
and the economic affairs minister Istvan Csillag has appointed a <br>
ministerial commissioner to coordinate the elimination of the <br>
operational failure. passage omitted <br>
<br>
Yesterday, 8 May, in its 0530 gmt bulletin, Pannon Radio quoted <br>
Zoltan Illes, who is the environmental spokesman of the senior <br>
opposition party Fidesz and also the deputy chairman of the <br>
parliamentary environmental protection committee, as saying that &quot;if <br>
the damaged (fuel) rods of Reactor No 2 are not removed from the tank <br>
soon, very serious consequences could follow&quot;. Interviewed by Tibor <br>
Franka of Pannon Radio, the politician said that, &quot;contrary to pro-<br>
government declarations, a chain reaction could start, leading to a <br>
disaster similar to that of Chernobyl because the cooling of the rods <br>
is insufficient&quot;. He urged that Reactor No 2 be covered by a <br>
sarcophagi made of concrete. Zoltan Illes said that the power <br>
station's management should be dismissed because the information they <br>
provided to the public was delayed and inaccurate.&quot; <br>
<br>
In the interview Zoltan Illes said that &quot;nuclear experts from the <br>
neighbouring countries and from other parts of the world must be <br>
asked to come to Hungary urgently and the Hungarian government must <br>
announce that it awaits for international help.&quot; Illes also &quot;begged&quot; <br>
for the immediate closing down of Reactor No 1 because it is in the <br>
same hall as Reactor No 2 where the accident took place and the <br>
decontaminating, purifying tank. He also called for the public to be <br>
trained to take emergency measures. <br>
<br>
It &quot;has always been on the cards&quot; that a chain reaction might <br>
occur &quot;since the transfer of the 30 fuel rods from the reactor, where <br>
the process could be managed in a controlled environment, to a tank <br>
which has had no protection; from that point on the management <br>
created an unmanageable reactor in which, if the critical mass builds <br>
up, a chain reaction could start immediately,&quot; he said, adding <br>
that &quot;the Hungarian government should focus on this and not on Iraq-<br>
related military matters or other things. For the immediate future, <br>
it is the most serious danger to the entire country, and not just to <br>
the country but to all people in the Carpathia Basin name used to <br>
depict territory of historic Hungary , whether they are Hungarian or <br>
not - and, as you have correctly said - to Europe.&quot; <br>
<br>
Illes said that &quot;it is no surprise, for example, that the Austrian <br>
government has been continuously protesting and that other <br>
international organizations say that the accident at Paks was much <br>
more serious than its grade on the nuclear accident scale would <br>
suggest&quot;. <br>
<br>
He accused the Paks management of having misled the public because <br>
when the accident occurred the level of radiation was &quot;much higher&quot; <br>
than the daily permitted radiation level whereas the Paks management <br>
said that this radiation level should be spread over a year. &quot;They <br>
are talking rubbish; nobody breathes on an annual average basis, or <br>
even daily average, but there and then, at that moment.&quot; <br>
<br>
He said that &quot;at the moment experts have been intimidated, experts <br>
who know the situation very well&quot;. Anyway, he added, &quot;it is a very <br>
small nuclear interest group which lives on handing the jobs to each <br>
other&quot;. <br>
<br>
Illes said that &quot;on 2 May, Nepszabadsag (largest circulation <br>
broadsheet) published an article by Szilvia Varro, which accurately <br>
described how well the insiders knew what had happened and how they <br>
tried to inform their families and acquaintances, warning them to <br>
close their windows, telling them that there was great trouble. The <br>
Paks management tried to suppress all of this.&quot; <br>
<br>
