Shall we be afraid of spontaneous nuclear chain reaction? One shouldn't and shall not be afraid of this either during the cleaning and the incident or in the days after.<br>
Prior to the commissioning of the cleaning equipment a safety report on the chain reaction occurrence as a consequence of potential incident was prepared by two specialized companies. Both studies calculations excluded this outcome. The visual inspection of damaged fuel assemblies being inside the cleaning tank and also the absence of chain reaction collateral phenomena (change of neutron radiation) prove clearly that no chain reaction took place during the incident.<br>
What is the situation like now? The cleaning tank is still inside the maintenance shaft. It's cooling provided by 4 pumps and the necessary data are recorded by additional measuring-control instruments. According to the calculations of two Hungarian research institute independent from each other the conditions are stabilized and the risk of spontaneous chain reaction can be excluded unambiguously. Several hundred operations are being performed by the plant personnel daily on Unit 2 shutdown for maintenance and being in operational condition and on the systems connected to the decay pool and the maintenance shaft. These actions, procedures are being applied repeatedly for over twenty years in compliance with the safety requirements. In the light of the serious incident occurred our activities are in the full glare of publicity.<br>
Some days ago we performed a chemical treatment operation during which we did not follow the approved program. Although it did not have any safety risk the persons involved in it were hold responsible.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
